@inproceedings{SchulteFortkamp2007,
    abstract = {Rhythm in music is the patterned, recurring alternations of contrasting elements of sound; the pattern or flow of sound. In landscape design the viewer's perspective is led beyond the foreground to a more distant part of the landscape, due to the way the landscape design "flows“. Rhythm in soundscape characterizes the time structure of the soundscape with its distinctive noise events embedded in comprehensive acoustical scenery. Soundscape can be considered as a dynamic system characterized by the time-dependent occurrence of particular sound events embedded in specific environments to describe ambiances and combine the daily recurrent patterns of sound multi-factorial in the process of analysis. The evaluation must reflect the continually varying acoustical scenery and its specific perception, whereby acoustic coloration from environmental noise sources carries information that may either block or stimulate human activities, thoughts, and feelings. It is a concert in soundscape assessment in acoustical but also other sensory, aesthetic, geographical, social, psychological and cultural modalities in the context of human activity across space, time, and society. Under scrutiny are three questions: how to capture the acoustic features of a soundscape, how to determine the unique rhythm of a soundscape, how to gather information about the listener’s perception of the soundscape?},
